00:03:29.170 --> 00:03:30.580
So last time, we
started to think

00:03:30.580 --> 00:03:35.495
about how to think about
discrete time systems.

00:03:35.495 --> 00:03:37.620
The thing you were supposed
to get out of last time

00:03:37.620 --> 00:03:39.480
is that there's
different representations

00:03:39.480 --> 00:03:40.710
for discrete time systems.

00:03:40.710 --> 00:03:43.740
We're interested in all of them.

00:03:43.740 --> 00:03:46.200
We're interested in all of
them because of the strengths

00:03:46.200 --> 00:03:47.820
and weaknesses of each.

00:03:47.820 --> 00:03:50.770
We looked particularly
at difference equations,

00:03:50.770 --> 00:03:54.270
which are mathematically
precise and concise.

00:03:54.270 --> 00:03:56.180
That's very good.

00:03:56.180 --> 00:03:57.930
We looked at block
diagrams, that was good

00:03:57.930 --> 00:04:02.100
because we could trace
the flow of information

00:04:02.100 --> 00:04:05.270
through the network.

00:04:05.270 --> 00:04:07.670
And we looked at
operator representations

00:04:07.670 --> 00:04:08.600
and they were nice.

00:04:08.600 --> 00:04:12.170
And we will see further
today how that's nice.

00:04:12.170 --> 00:04:13.670
They are nice
because they allow us

00:04:13.670 --> 00:04:19.230
to think about a system in
terms of polynomial mathematics.

00:04:19.230 --> 00:04:21.390
So what I want to
do today primarily

00:04:21.390 --> 00:04:22.945
is develop that latter theme.

00:04:25.950 --> 00:04:30.300
Keep in mind that one of the
important features of the block

00:04:30.300 --> 00:04:32.470
diagram was the arrow notation.

00:04:32.470 --> 00:04:34.020
It told you what causes what.

00:04:34.020 --> 00:04:36.885
It let you make a hardware
realization of a system.

00:04:39.620 --> 00:04:42.290
An important point from last
time, which we just ended on

00:04:42.290 --> 00:04:45.580
at the end of the hour,
an important point

00:04:45.580 --> 00:04:49.270
was that when you're
thinking about the signals,

00:04:49.270 --> 00:04:51.190
there's a higher
level abstraction that

00:04:51.190 --> 00:04:53.980
is also important.

00:04:53.980 --> 00:04:56.830
In addition to knowing which
is the input to the R operator

00:04:56.830 --> 00:04:59.290
and which is the output
of the R operator,

00:04:59.290 --> 00:05:01.120
there are some kinds
of systems that

00:05:01.120 --> 00:05:03.610
just behave categorically
different from other kinds

00:05:03.610 --> 00:05:04.540
of systems.

00:05:04.540 --> 00:05:06.580
And they are indicated here.

00:05:06.580 --> 00:05:09.400
This system has
the property that

00:05:09.400 --> 00:05:14.320
is easy to write a recipe
for how to compute y given x.

00:05:14.320 --> 00:05:15.670
How do you compute y given x?

00:05:15.670 --> 00:05:21.700
Well, you take x,
copy it, invert it,

00:05:21.700 --> 00:05:23.470
shift it to the right.

00:05:23.470 --> 00:05:27.580
Add the copy to the
inverted shifted.

00:05:27.580 --> 00:05:29.560
Easy to make a
recipe to do that.

00:05:29.560 --> 00:05:31.780
It's not so easy to
make a recipe here.

00:05:35.610 --> 00:05:36.110
Right?

00:05:36.110 --> 00:05:38.750
So there, so if
you think about how

00:05:38.750 --> 00:05:42.770
you would try to write that in
an operator, you could say, y.

00:05:42.770 --> 00:05:43.640
What is y?

00:05:43.640 --> 00:05:47.160
y is going to be x plus
a right-shift of y.

00:05:50.170 --> 00:05:53.920
So you could say, well that's 1
minus a right-shift of y equals

00:05:53.920 --> 00:05:54.850
x.

00:05:54.850 --> 00:05:59.380
That's not a recipe
for computing y from x.

00:05:59.380 --> 00:06:03.330
That's a recipe for
computing x from y.

00:06:03.330 --> 00:06:05.487
But we don't know y.

00:06:05.487 --> 00:06:06.070
Everybody see?

00:06:06.070 --> 00:06:08.420
That's completely different.

00:06:08.420 --> 00:06:11.090
And so it's that
difference that makes

00:06:11.090 --> 00:06:13.130
this kind of a
network, this kind

00:06:13.130 --> 00:06:18.770
of a system interesting
by comparison to that one.

00:06:18.770 --> 00:06:23.510
And the distinguishing feature
that makes that behavior occur

00:06:23.510 --> 00:06:26.600
is feedback.

00:06:26.600 --> 00:06:30.230
When you have feedback,
feedback means,

00:06:30.230 --> 00:06:32.600
for some signal
in the system, we

00:06:32.600 --> 00:06:34.160
would say the
system has feedback

00:06:34.160 --> 00:06:38.600
if there is some signal
somewhere whose output at time

00:06:38.600 --> 00:06:44.780
n depends on it's same, the
output of that same signal

00:06:44.780 --> 00:06:47.810
at a previous time.

00:06:47.810 --> 00:06:52.040
If that's true for some
signal in the system,

00:06:52.040 --> 00:06:56.240
then we say the
system has feedback.

00:06:56.240 --> 00:07:00.150
The implications of
feedback are profound.

00:07:00.150 --> 00:07:03.950
They mean, for example, that a
transient input can give rise

00:07:03.950 --> 00:07:05.735
to a persisting output.

00:07:05.735 --> 00:07:07.610
And we took a look at
how to think about that

00:07:07.610 --> 00:07:09.920
in terms of the block diagrams.

00:07:09.920 --> 00:07:13.190
You can see that if you had
even a signal that only lasts

00:07:13.190 --> 00:07:16.430
for one sample, a signal--

00:07:16.430 --> 00:07:19.250
a system that has this
property of feedback

00:07:19.250 --> 00:07:24.050
could generate a response that
lasts for a very long time.

00:07:24.050 --> 00:07:28.000
In fact, the response at time 0,
the only way that could happen

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:29.770
is through the
straight through path.

00:07:29.770 --> 00:07:32.560
The only way you could get
an output at time 0, given

00:07:32.560 --> 00:07:35.700
that the input is non-0 only
at 0 is through the straight

00:07:35.700 --> 00:07:37.240
through path.

00:07:37.240 --> 00:07:39.550
But then you could get
an output at time 1

00:07:39.550 --> 00:07:42.170
if you cycled around once.

00:07:42.170 --> 00:07:44.570
This is the idea that a
signal somewhere depends

00:07:44.570 --> 00:07:48.160
on a prior value of itself.

00:07:48.160 --> 00:07:50.940
And you could get a
response at time 2

00:07:50.940 --> 00:07:53.940
by going around the loop
twice, three, 3 times, 4,

00:07:53.940 --> 00:07:55.970
four times, et cetera.

00:07:55.970 --> 00:08:00.300
And in general, the response
could persist forever.

00:08:00.300 --> 00:08:02.220
That's such an
interesting behavior.

00:08:02.220 --> 00:08:04.950
It's such a fundamental
property of these systems

00:08:04.950 --> 00:08:07.320
that we want to
characterize systems

00:08:07.320 --> 00:08:10.550
by thinking about them that way.

00:08:10.550 --> 00:08:14.410
So in this particular
case, if we

00:08:14.410 --> 00:08:16.570
think about sort of
the most simple form

00:08:16.570 --> 00:08:19.060
that feedback
could take, this is

00:08:19.060 --> 00:08:22.420
sort of the simplest
way you could imagine.

00:08:22.420 --> 00:08:23.950
This is kind of
the simplest system

00:08:23.950 --> 00:08:25.658
that you could imagine
that has feedback.

00:08:28.310 --> 00:08:31.900
And you can see that the kinds
of responses that you can get

00:08:31.900 --> 00:08:34.720
depend on this number p-naught.

00:08:34.720 --> 00:08:38.080
And that p-naught characterizes
the family of responses

00:08:38.080 --> 00:08:39.919
that you could get.

00:08:39.919 --> 00:08:44.900
So for example, if p-naught
were a number less than 1,

00:08:44.900 --> 00:08:49.250
you could get a decaying
geometric sequence.

00:08:49.250 --> 00:08:53.060
If p-naught were 1 exactly,
you would get a response

00:08:53.060 --> 00:08:56.870
that never decayed or grew.

00:08:56.870 --> 00:08:59.360
And if p-naught were a
number bigger than 1,

00:08:59.360 --> 00:09:01.557
then the response
could grow infinitely.

00:09:01.557 --> 00:09:03.390
So that's a very
fundamental characteristic.

00:09:03.390 --> 00:09:07.711
And we call that number
p-naught the pole.

00:09:07.711 --> 00:09:08.210
OK.

00:09:08.210 --> 00:09:09.376
Everybody's happy with that?

00:09:09.376 --> 00:09:11.170
That's very simple-minded.

00:09:11.170 --> 00:09:14.800
So we're going to
characterize-- so the point is,

00:09:14.800 --> 00:09:19.690
there's a higher level
of structure in systems

00:09:19.690 --> 00:09:20.940
that we would like to capture.

00:09:20.940 --> 00:09:23.550
We're going to call that
higher level feedback.

00:09:23.550 --> 00:09:26.640
It means there's a cycle
in the block diagram.

00:09:26.640 --> 00:09:31.140
And it means that you can get
characteristically different

00:09:31.140 --> 00:09:35.370
kinds of responses then result
when you don't have feedback.

00:09:35.370 --> 00:09:37.350
In particular,
simple systems will

00:09:37.350 --> 00:09:39.660
