00:14:59.450 --> 00:15:00.710
That's not quite true.

00:15:00.710 --> 00:15:02.030
Let me retract that slightly.

00:15:02.030 --> 00:15:05.540
Here are some-- and I will
make this more complicated

00:15:05.540 --> 00:15:08.780
and about two pages of notes.

00:15:08.780 --> 00:15:14.040
Here's all the real values of
p-naught and the associated

00:15:14.040 --> 00:15:15.140
behaviors.

00:15:15.140 --> 00:15:18.500
In two pages, we'll get to the
complex values for p-naught.

00:15:18.500 --> 00:15:20.970
So here's all of
that the responses

00:15:20.970 --> 00:15:28.840
that can be associated with
a single real valued pole.

00:15:28.840 --> 00:15:31.210
So you can get, as
somebody has already said,

00:15:31.210 --> 00:15:36.880
you can get the idea of
diverging with alternation,

00:15:36.880 --> 00:15:41.140
converging with alternation,
converging monotonically,

00:15:41.140 --> 00:15:42.600
diverging monotonically.

00:15:42.600 --> 00:15:45.431
Those are the behaviors you can
get with a single real value

00:15:45.431 --> 00:15:45.930
pole.

00:15:48.810 --> 00:15:50.110
OK.

00:15:50.110 --> 00:15:52.710
That's what can happen with
a single real valued pole

00:15:52.710 --> 00:15:56.327
but systems, there are
more complicated systems.

00:15:56.327 --> 00:15:58.160
And when you have a
more complicated system,

00:15:58.160 --> 00:16:00.110
you can get a more
complicated response.

00:16:00.110 --> 00:16:01.940
And one example is shown here.

00:16:01.940 --> 00:16:03.930
So here a system.

00:16:03.930 --> 00:16:06.320
Here's the unit-sample response.

00:16:06.320 --> 00:16:10.910
Is this something that can be
represented by a single pole?

00:16:10.910 --> 00:16:14.350
No, because it doesn't fall into
one of those canonical shapes.

00:16:14.350 --> 00:16:15.080
Right.

00:16:15.080 --> 00:16:17.940
In fact, this response
has the property

00:16:17.940 --> 00:16:21.670
that it grows and then decays.

00:16:21.670 --> 00:16:24.070
But it only does the
grow and decay once,

00:16:24.070 --> 00:16:25.950
so it's just not one
of the canonical forms.

00:16:25.950 --> 00:16:28.450
So now there's something
different going on here

00:16:28.450 --> 00:16:30.380
and we'd like to
understand what that is.

00:16:30.380 --> 00:16:34.280
So we cannot represent
that by a single pole.

00:16:34.280 --> 00:16:38.890
However, this is where the
polynomial stuff becomes useful

00:16:38.890 --> 00:16:41.200
because I can think
about tricks I

00:16:41.200 --> 00:16:43.060
can do with the
polynomials, which you all

00:16:43.060 --> 00:16:45.672
learned in high school so
you all know how to do that.

00:16:45.672 --> 00:16:50.461
That we can think about
the system in terms of,

00:16:50.461 --> 00:16:52.210
we can think about
this complicated system

00:16:52.210 --> 00:16:56.140
in terms of simpler systems that
can be represented by one pole.

00:16:56.140 --> 00:16:59.200
So for example, one of
the more powerful things

00:16:59.200 --> 00:17:01.180
you can do with a
polynomial is factor.

00:17:01.180 --> 00:17:04.599
If you factor this polynomial--

00:17:04.599 --> 00:17:06.849
OK, so this is a simple
representation for that right?

00:17:06.849 --> 00:17:10.520
I can just read
that straight off.

00:17:10.520 --> 00:17:12.619
So I can make this
representation just reading it

00:17:12.619 --> 00:17:14.510
straight off the block diagram.

00:17:14.510 --> 00:17:18.240
I can turn that into an operator
type representation here.

00:17:18.240 --> 00:17:22.109
So I operate on y with
this mass to get x.

00:17:22.109 --> 00:17:26.450
It's backwards feedback,
that's what happens.

00:17:26.450 --> 00:17:28.560
But the second order
polynomial in R

00:17:28.560 --> 00:17:32.850
can be factored into two
first order polynomials in R.

00:17:32.850 --> 00:17:34.800
And not surprisingly,
that then leads

00:17:34.800 --> 00:17:38.430
to a representation of the
more complex system in terms

00:17:38.430 --> 00:17:40.900
of two simpler systems.

00:17:40.900 --> 00:17:44.460
So in fact, I can write
the original system.

00:17:44.460 --> 00:17:47.550
If I factor it, there's an
equivalent representation.

00:17:47.550 --> 00:17:52.390
Equivalent means provided
that all the systems

00:17:52.390 --> 00:17:53.830
start initial rest.

00:17:53.830 --> 00:17:59.320
Initial rest means provided all
the delays started out at 0.

00:17:59.320 --> 00:18:01.210
Putting in the
normal caveats, there

00:18:01.210 --> 00:18:03.710
is an equivalent representation
to the complex system.

00:18:03.710 --> 00:18:07.680
In fact, there's two
equivalent systems shown here.

00:18:07.680 --> 00:18:10.500
Each corresponds to factoring.

00:18:10.500 --> 00:18:13.440
And it corresponds to
doing which factor first.

00:18:13.440 --> 00:18:15.030
So in the first
realization, it says

00:18:15.030 --> 00:18:17.610
that generate an
intermediate signal

00:18:17.610 --> 00:18:21.204
by thinking about the factor
that has a base of 0.7.

00:18:21.204 --> 00:18:25.650
Then cascade that with
another system that

00:18:25.650 --> 00:18:31.210
has a base that looks just like
a canonical first order system,

00:18:31.210 --> 00:18:33.670
except that the base now is 0.9.

00:18:33.670 --> 00:18:37.060
And presumably, if you
cascade those two things,

00:18:37.060 --> 00:18:40.250
you will get an
equivalent response.

00:18:40.250 --> 00:18:42.235
And the order didn't
make any difference.

00:18:44.890 --> 00:18:48.550
So that's a way we can
think about the response

00:18:48.550 --> 00:18:52.220
of a more complex system in
terms of first order responses.

00:18:52.220 --> 00:18:55.430
So that's nice.

00:18:55.430 --> 00:18:58.020
And that gives us then--

00:18:58.020 --> 00:19:03.560
so we can then use the idea
of the Taylor series expansion

00:19:03.560 --> 00:19:06.980
to think about the response
of each of those first order

00:19:06.980 --> 00:19:11.600
systems, so we can replace the
response of the canonical first

00:19:11.600 --> 00:19:17.030
order system with the infinite
feedforward realization--

00:19:17.030 --> 00:19:21.110
remember from last time, the
first order feedback system can

00:19:21.110 --> 00:19:24.120
be equivalently represented
by an infinite order

00:19:24.120 --> 00:19:27.540
of feedforward system--

00:19:27.540 --> 00:19:30.880
so that the unit-sample
response here.

00:19:30.880 --> 00:19:34.800
So this system, excuse me, this
first order feedback system

00:19:34.800 --> 00:19:40.350
can be rewritten as that
infinite order feedforward

00:19:40.350 --> 00:19:41.280
system.

00:19:41.280 --> 00:19:43.740
This one can be
written that way.

00:19:43.740 --> 00:19:48.210
And then again, we can
use polynomial math

00:19:48.210 --> 00:19:52.210
to figure out the response of
that more complicated system.

00:19:52.210 --> 00:19:55.500
All we need to do is multiply
and then collect terms.

00:19:55.500 --> 00:19:57.510
You all know how to
multiply polynomials,

00:19:57.510 --> 00:20:01.160
therefore you all know how to
solve second order systems.

00:20:01.160 --> 00:20:01.660
OK.

00:20:01.660 --> 00:20:04.630
That's the advantage of
converting one representation,

00:20:04.630 --> 00:20:07.112
a system representation, into
a polynomial representation

00:20:07.112 --> 00:20:09.070
because you already know
all about polynomials.

00:20:09.070 --> 00:20:11.440
Since you already know how
to multiply polynomials,

00:20:11.440 --> 00:20:13.420
you already know how
to cascade systems.

00:20:17.150 --> 00:20:22.450
The only difficulty
here is bookkeeping,

00:20:22.450 --> 00:20:23.560
not missing a term.

00:20:23.560 --> 00:20:25.900
So there are graphic
aids to that.

00:20:25.900 --> 00:20:27.670
Think about the
block diagram that

00:20:27.670 --> 00:20:32.200
would correspond to the
infinite feedforward realization

00:20:32.200 --> 00:20:37.910
of the left part and
the infinite feedforward

00:20:37.910 --> 00:20:40.540
realization of the right part.

00:20:40.540 --> 00:20:45.290
So I'm thinking about this
system and that system being

00:20:45.290 --> 00:20:46.940
represented by this
infinite system

00:20:46.940 --> 00:20:48.740
and that infinite system.

00:20:48.740 --> 00:20:52.430
And now just making a block
diagram realization of this

00:20:52.430 --> 00:20:54.920
and a separate block
diagram realization of that

00:20:54.920 --> 00:20:56.365
and cascading them to get this.

00:20:59.540 --> 00:21:01.740
And now the
bookkeeping is trivial.

00:21:01.740 --> 00:21:05.460
What's the only way you can
get a response if the input is

00:21:05.460 --> 00:21:07.500
a unit-sample signal?

00:21:07.500 --> 00:21:10.440
What's the only way you can get
a response at time n equals 0?

00:21:13.950 --> 00:21:16.740
What's the only signal path
that generates a response of n

00:21:16.740 --> 00:21:17.250
equals 0?

00:21:22.940 --> 00:21:23.846
Say it louder?

00:21:23.846 --> 00:21:25.370
AUDIENCE: The top right left.

00:21:25.370 --> 00:21:26.870
DENNIS FREEMAN: The
only signal path

00:21:26.870 --> 00:21:29.600
is to go through here, because
if I go through here, I

00:21:29.600 --> 00:21:30.470
introduce a delay.

00:21:30.470 --> 00:21:31.970
This introduces even more delay.

00:21:31.970 --> 00:21:33.639
This introduces even more delay.

00:21:33.639 --> 00:21:35.180
The only way I can
get from the input

00:21:35.180 --> 00:21:39.260
to the output with no delay
is to go through the one

00:21:39.260 --> 00:21:42.320
here and go through
the one here.

00:21:42.320 --> 00:21:44.769
So that that's where
that term comes from.

00:21:44.769 --> 00:21:46.310
The only way I can
get from the input

00:21:46.310 --> 00:21:51.000
to the output with no delay,
no R, is through that top path.

00:21:51.000 --> 00:21:53.200
If I want to get
one level of delay,

00:21:53.200 --> 00:21:56.250
the only way I can do that is
to pick it up here and then not

00:21:56.250 --> 00:21:57.690
pick it up there or vice versa.

00:22:00.550 --> 00:22:05.050
There's more ways that
I could get two delays.

00:22:05.050 --> 00:22:06.670
I can pick up two
delays all at once

00:22:06.670 --> 00:22:10.390
on the left with none on
the right or vice versa

00:22:10.390 --> 00:22:12.310
or one in each.

00:22:12.310 --> 00:22:14.260
That's just bookkeeping, right?

00:22:14.260 --> 00:22:15.760
It's just showing
you how you can

00:22:15.760 --> 00:22:17.950
think about polynomial
multiplication

00:22:17.950 --> 00:22:21.130
in different ways.

00:22:21.130 --> 00:22:25.589
Alternatively, you could
represent it in a table.

00:22:25.589 --> 00:22:27.380
So if you think about
multiplying these two

00:22:27.380 --> 00:22:30.200
polynomials where I've
represented the first pole as a

00:22:30.200 --> 00:22:35.460
in the second pole
as b, you can think

00:22:35.460 --> 00:22:38.940
about polynomial multiplication
in a tabular form.

00:22:38.940 --> 00:22:41.610
So you have to think about
the distributive property,

00:22:41.610 --> 00:22:43.630
the 1 distributes
over all of these,

00:22:43.630 --> 00:22:45.570
then the a distributes
over all, the aR

00:22:45.570 --> 00:22:48.000
distributes over all of these
and the a-squared R-squared

00:22:48.000 --> 00:22:50.430
distributes over all of these.

00:22:50.430 --> 00:22:53.760
And you can represent each of
those distribution operations

00:22:53.760 --> 00:22:55.320
by a row in the table.

00:22:55.320 --> 00:22:58.230
And then you can see
that the only entries

00:22:58.230 --> 00:23:02.370
with no R, with R to the
0 is along that diagonal.

00:23:02.370 --> 00:23:04.790
And then the R terms are
here, the R-squared terms,

00:23:04.790 --> 00:23:07.434
the R-cubed terms, et cetera.

00:23:07.434 --> 00:23:08.850
And you can see
how that would all

00:23:08.850 --> 00:23:13.140
sum to give you something
that's not a geometric.

00:23:13.140 --> 00:23:15.470
OK, all those things,
just bookkeeping.

00:23:15.470 --> 00:23:16.040
Right?

00:23:16.040 --> 00:23:17.600
All I'm trying to say
is that there is a way

00:23:17.600 --> 00:23:19.940
that you can think about the
second order system which

00:23:19.940 --> 00:23:24.170
does not generate a simple
geometric sequence by thinking

00:23:24.170 --> 00:23:27.290
about the cascade of
two systems that each

00:23:27.290 --> 00:23:34.540
do generate a unit-sample
response that is geometric.

00:23:34.540 --> 00:23:36.970
Nevertheless, all of
this is bookkeeping.

00:23:36.970 --> 00:23:39.254
It's still the case that
this is a complicated shape.

00:23:39.254 --> 00:23:41.170
And you still have to
do a fair amount of work

00:23:41.170 --> 00:23:43.870
to figure out what that
complicated shape is.

00:23:43.870 --> 00:23:46.840
We can use polynomials
one more time

00:23:46.840 --> 00:23:48.490
to make it conceptually simpler.

00:23:51.940 --> 00:23:56.100
We can do something that
we call partial fractions.

00:23:56.100 --> 00:23:58.050
You can take the
expression that we

00:23:58.050 --> 00:24:01.450
found for this
complicated system,

00:24:01.450 --> 00:24:04.520
factor it just
like we did before.

00:24:04.520 --> 00:24:07.880
But now, according to the
method of partial fractions,

00:24:07.880 --> 00:24:11.780
you can represent the
reciprocal of a quadratic

00:24:11.780 --> 00:24:15.260
as the sum of two terms,
each the reciprocal

00:24:15.260 --> 00:24:20.220
of a linear function in R.
So you can always do that.

00:24:20.220 --> 00:24:24.750
That's a property of
polynomials, right?

00:24:24.750 --> 00:24:27.750
So what that says is that
there's an equivalent

00:24:27.750 --> 00:24:34.206
representation for this
complicated system that

00:24:34.206 --> 00:24:37.670
looks like this.

00:24:37.670 --> 00:24:43.970
So backing up, so we showed
that by factoring, we

00:24:43.970 --> 00:24:46.070
take this and turn it into this.

00:24:46.070 --> 00:24:49.460
By partial fractions we turn
it into a sum difference.

00:24:49.460 --> 00:24:51.600
What's the difference?

00:24:51.600 --> 00:24:54.120
So now we think about
that difference here.

00:24:56.730 --> 00:25:00.980
This term can be generated
by multiplying 4.5 times

00:25:00.980 --> 00:25:03.385
a canonic first order term.

00:25:06.180 --> 00:25:10.380
This can be generated
by multiplying minus 3.5

00:25:10.380 --> 00:25:13.610
times a canonic
first order term.

00:25:13.610 --> 00:25:16.590
And the response adds.

00:25:16.590 --> 00:25:20.960
OK, well that's
completely new insight.

00:25:20.960 --> 00:25:24.170
We've taken what looks like
a very complicated response

00:25:24.170 --> 00:25:27.360
from a system that is
not a canonical form.

00:25:27.360 --> 00:25:28.940
And we've turned
it into something

00:25:28.940 --> 00:25:33.224
that does look like
several canonical forms,

00:25:33.224 --> 00:25:34.640
just like we did
with the cascade,

00:25:34.640 --> 00:25:37.940
but now we can see
that the answer is

00:25:37.940 --> 00:25:40.100
the sum of two geometrics.

00:25:44.157 --> 00:25:44.990
Everybody's with it?

00:25:44.990 --> 00:25:50.270
So it's even better than
being able to cascade,

00:25:50.270 --> 00:25:54.340
wherein the cascade, we have to
do some complicated bookkeeping

00:25:54.340 --> 00:25:56.470
in order to figure
out the responses.

00:25:56.470 --> 00:25:59.260
By thinking about it
with partial fractions,

00:25:59.260 --> 00:26:02.621
it's the simple sum
of two simple things.

00:26:02.621 --> 00:26:04.870
So then if you know properties
of each individual one,

00:26:04.870 --> 00:26:07.120
life it rattles for
a long time or it

00:26:07.120 --> 00:26:11.470
decays quickly, you can
instantly say something

00:26:11.470 --> 00:26:14.670
about the combined response.

00:26:14.670 --> 00:26:17.150
Does that follow?

00:26:17.150 --> 00:26:20.540
So then this response,
which I introduced

00:26:20.540 --> 00:26:23.090
by saying it's complicated,
it's not really complicated.

00:26:23.090 --> 00:26:24.680
It's the sum of two geometrics.

00:26:28.320 --> 00:26:31.030
It goes up and then down simply
because the decay constants

00:26:31.030 --> 00:26:33.570
for the two different geometrics
are different, that's all.

00:26:36.680 --> 00:26:41.660
The point is that this
is a very different kind

00:26:41.660 --> 00:26:43.820
of representation.

00:26:43.820 --> 00:26:46.670
Many things-- so
you could do a lot

00:26:46.670 --> 00:26:49.400
by just taking a
difference equation

00:26:49.400 --> 00:26:52.340
and just factoring it and moving
terms around and figuring out

00:26:52.340 --> 00:26:57.170
different ways to do the
sums and so forth to try

00:26:57.170 --> 00:26:58.924
to simplify your life.

00:26:58.924 --> 00:27:00.590
You can do the same
with block diagrams.

00:27:00.590 --> 00:27:02.048
You could shuffle
around the blocks

00:27:02.048 --> 00:27:04.130
and try to make things simpler.

00:27:04.130 --> 00:27:09.720
This idea of turning
the top system into this

00:27:09.720 --> 00:27:13.320
is trivial to see with
polynomial manipulations

00:27:13.320 --> 00:27:16.650
and relatively and not at
all straightforward to do

00:27:16.650 --> 00:27:19.230
by simple block
diagram manipulations.

00:27:19.230 --> 00:27:22.200
It follows directly from
the polynomial realization.

00:27:22.200 --> 00:27:24.750
That's what we mean by a
more powerful representation.

00:27:24.750 --> 00:27:28.150
It's very easy to see how we
got there if you represent

00:27:28.150 --> 00:27:29.340
the system by a polynomial.

00:27:29.340 --> 00:27:32.006
It's much less easy to
see how we got there

00:27:32.006 --> 00:27:33.630
by thinking about it
as a block diagram

00:27:33.630 --> 00:27:36.500
or as a difference equation.

00:27:36.500 --> 00:27:37.436
OK?

00:27:37.436 --> 00:27:37.935
Makes sense?

00:27:42.560 --> 00:27:45.680
Because they're so important,
we would like shorthand ways

00:27:45.680 --> 00:27:46.630
of finding poles.

00:27:49.092 --> 00:27:51.050
As soon as you know the
poles of a system, then

00:27:51.050 --> 00:27:53.540
you know the geometric
sequences that characterize

00:27:53.540 --> 00:27:55.610
unit-sample response.

00:27:55.610 --> 00:27:58.200
And for at least a
broad class of systems,

00:27:58.200 --> 00:28:01.490
we're going to be able to
think about the combined

00:28:01.490 --> 00:28:06.200
unit-sample responses of the
system as some weighted sum

00:28:06.200 --> 00:28:10.750
of individual contributions.

00:28:10.750 --> 00:28:12.310
So that makes the
idea of finding

00:28:12.310 --> 00:28:14.374
the pose very important.

00:28:14.374 --> 00:28:15.790
There's a very
straightforward way

00:28:15.790 --> 00:28:17.960
that we've sort of
already alluded to.

00:28:17.960 --> 00:28:19.360
If you had this
complicated thing

00:28:19.360 --> 00:28:23.170
and you wanted to find the
poles, what you should do

00:28:23.170 --> 00:28:25.930
is try to coerce it
into the canonical form.

00:28:25.930 --> 00:28:32.500
You remember the canonic
form for a single pole system

00:28:32.500 --> 00:28:34.790
was this sort of representation.

00:28:40.880 --> 00:28:42.360
So you have x coming in.

00:28:42.360 --> 00:28:45.780
Coming out as y and
feeding around that way.

00:28:45.780 --> 00:28:50.880
That's the canonical
form for one pole system.

00:28:50.880 --> 00:28:53.610
And that had a system
function of the form y

00:28:53.610 --> 00:29:01.730
over x is 1 over 1
minus p-naught R.

00:29:01.730 --> 00:29:07.220
So if you can coerce all the
parts to look like 1 over 1

00:29:07.220 --> 00:29:11.480
minus p-naught R then according
to that, here's a pole

00:29:11.480 --> 00:29:14.210
and there's a pole
just by canonic forms

00:29:14.210 --> 00:29:16.730
and matching up the terms
in a canonic form, right?

00:29:20.570 --> 00:29:24.830
That requires some sort of
graphic memory or something

00:29:24.830 --> 00:29:29.120
graphic ability to take one form
and turn it into another form.

00:29:29.120 --> 00:29:33.680
A simpler rule is to
say, look, just replace

00:29:33.680 --> 00:29:38.970
all the Rs by 1 over
z, rewrite things,

00:29:38.970 --> 00:29:41.420
and the z's turn out to be--

00:29:41.420 --> 00:29:43.850
the values of z that are
the roots of the denominator

00:29:43.850 --> 00:29:46.320
turn out to be the
values of the poles.

00:29:46.320 --> 00:29:48.230
That's very
straightforward to see just

00:29:48.230 --> 00:29:50.360
by looking at the
canonical form.

00:29:50.360 --> 00:29:51.890
If I have the
canonical form where

00:29:51.890 --> 00:29:58.540
I know that the pole is p-naught
and if I replaced the R by 1

00:29:58.540 --> 00:30:02.080
over z and cleared
the fraction, I

00:30:02.080 --> 00:30:04.940
would end up with z
over z minus p-naught.

00:30:04.940 --> 00:30:08.290
And now if I ask what's the
poles at the bottom, what's

00:30:08.290 --> 00:30:09.670
the roots of the bottom?

00:30:09.670 --> 00:30:14.170
For what values of z is
the denominator equal to 0?

00:30:14.170 --> 00:30:17.650
The answer is clearly
z equals p-naught.

00:30:17.650 --> 00:30:23.840
It's just a trick to turn a
system function in terms of R

00:30:23.840 --> 00:30:29.400
into a root-finding problem.

00:30:29.400 --> 00:30:31.510
So rather than having
some program that

00:30:31.510 --> 00:30:33.940
knows how to write
canonical forms,

00:30:33.940 --> 00:30:40.480
you can use any root finder to
find the values of the poles.

