00:41:17.150 --> 00:41:18.110
That's pretty weird.

00:41:21.960 --> 00:41:23.946
Also notice that
it doesn't behave

00:41:23.946 --> 00:41:25.320
the way we think
about it when we

00:41:25.320 --> 00:41:27.370
think about computer science.

00:41:27.370 --> 00:41:30.270
There's no r-squared
growth of anything.

00:41:30.270 --> 00:41:32.190
How many operations
is required to compute

00:41:32.190 --> 00:41:33.690
the output at time 119?

00:41:36.987 --> 00:41:39.350
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
operations.

00:41:39.350 --> 00:41:41.641
DENNIS FREEMAN: Depends on
what you mean by operations,

00:41:41.641 --> 00:41:42.540
that's a good point.

00:41:42.540 --> 00:41:47.801
So if you used a modern
laptop, how many steps

00:41:47.801 --> 00:41:49.050
would the laptop have to take?

00:41:52.800 --> 00:41:55.680
You have to know something
about what's inside the laptop.

00:41:55.680 --> 00:41:58.065
These days, exponentiation
is pretty simple.

00:42:00.760 --> 00:42:01.930
So you can think about--

00:42:01.930 --> 00:42:04.440
so all you need
to do is raise phi

00:42:04.440 --> 00:42:11.080
to the n an add
minus phi the minus n

00:42:11.080 --> 00:42:12.820
and scale them and add them.

00:42:12.820 --> 00:42:15.070
So it's a different way
of thinking about things.

00:42:15.070 --> 00:42:16.120
That's the point.

00:42:16.120 --> 00:42:19.690
So you can think about the
Fibonacci system as a recursion

00:42:19.690 --> 00:42:21.460
problem like we
did in 601 or you

00:42:21.460 --> 00:42:23.380
can think about
it as the response

00:42:23.380 --> 00:42:26.380
to an LTI system, a linear
time invariant system

00:42:26.380 --> 00:42:30.440
and you get this kind of a
way of thinking about things.

00:42:30.440 --> 00:42:33.660
OK one more thing
to talk about today.

00:42:33.660 --> 00:42:37.200
And that is, what happens
when things are complex?

00:42:37.200 --> 00:42:39.420
You can make a terribly
small change to the system

00:42:39.420 --> 00:42:40.770
functional.

00:42:40.770 --> 00:42:45.240
Here all I've done is change one
sign from the Fibonacci system

00:42:45.240 --> 00:42:49.330
and the result is complex roots.

00:42:49.330 --> 00:42:54.950
So what's it mean to have a
system that has complex poles?

00:42:54.950 --> 00:43:01.270
So complex poles, one of
the interesting things

00:43:01.270 --> 00:43:04.390
about polynomial
math, complex numbers

00:43:04.390 --> 00:43:06.990
work like any other number.

00:43:06.990 --> 00:43:10.500
Not surprisingly then, complex
poles in a linear system

00:43:10.500 --> 00:43:13.410
work sort of like
any other pole.

00:43:13.410 --> 00:43:16.170
The fundamental mode
associated with any pole

00:43:16.170 --> 00:43:19.320
is p-naught to the n.

00:43:19.320 --> 00:43:23.340
The fundamental modes
corresponding to a complex pole

00:43:23.340 --> 00:43:24.960
have complex values.

00:43:24.960 --> 00:43:27.190
And that's shown here.

00:43:27.190 --> 00:43:30.810
We can write-- so we can think
about that system polynomial

00:43:30.810 --> 00:43:32.310
that I showed in
the previous slide.

00:43:32.310 --> 00:43:34.080
This one.

00:43:34.080 --> 00:43:36.085
We can write that
in a factored form.

00:43:38.970 --> 00:43:41.345
But now, the roots
are complex numbers.

00:43:43.799 --> 00:43:44.840
This is a complex number.

00:43:44.840 --> 00:43:46.280
There's complex numbers
all over the place.

00:43:46.280 --> 00:43:46.780
Who cares?

00:43:46.780 --> 00:43:48.740
Complex numbers,
they're just numbers.

00:43:48.740 --> 00:43:51.120
That's the nice
part about algebra.

00:43:51.120 --> 00:43:53.980
So we don't need to
worry about that.

00:43:53.980 --> 00:43:56.430
Other than the
modes are complex.

00:43:56.430 --> 00:43:59.240
So if you try to plot
the mode associated

00:43:59.240 --> 00:44:03.550
with one of the roots
and the other root,

00:44:03.550 --> 00:44:06.160
they have real and
imaginary parts.

00:44:06.160 --> 00:44:08.530
So here I'm showing
the real part in blue

00:44:08.530 --> 00:44:12.150
and the imaginary part in red.

00:44:12.150 --> 00:44:14.960
So each of the fundamental modes
has a real and imaginary part.

00:44:14.960 --> 00:44:16.683
That's the only
complicated thing.

00:44:19.930 --> 00:44:26.240
It's sometimes easier
to visualize the modes

00:44:26.240 --> 00:44:29.600
on a polar plot.

00:44:29.600 --> 00:44:31.370
And that's illustrated here.

00:44:31.370 --> 00:44:34.200
These plots look complicated.

00:44:34.200 --> 00:44:37.850
If you think about what they
look like in polar coordinates.

00:44:37.850 --> 00:44:39.950
If you think about
this p-naught to the n,

00:44:39.950 --> 00:44:43.340
but now p-naught
is complex, just

00:44:43.340 --> 00:44:48.260
plot the number p-naught to
the n on a complex plane,

00:44:48.260 --> 00:44:49.610
it's pretty simple.

00:44:49.610 --> 00:44:55.175
So in this first case,
we have this pole at e

00:44:55.175 --> 00:44:57.590
to the j and pi over 3.

00:44:57.590 --> 00:45:00.380
Gets raised to the n-th power.

00:45:00.380 --> 00:45:01.970
And we use trig
and we can come up

00:45:01.970 --> 00:45:04.040
with some expression for that.

00:45:04.040 --> 00:45:08.330
But forget trig, just remember
the Euler relationship.

00:45:08.330 --> 00:45:09.530
And that's equivalent.

00:45:09.530 --> 00:45:12.350
We can just use this form
to say well, if you had 0,

00:45:12.350 --> 00:45:13.740
e to the 0 is 1.

00:45:13.740 --> 00:45:15.750
So I'm there.

00:45:15.750 --> 00:45:18.670
If n were 1, then it would
be e to the j pi over 3.

00:45:18.670 --> 00:45:19.850
Well, that's there.

00:45:19.850 --> 00:45:22.540
You go up by 60 degrees.

00:45:22.540 --> 00:45:23.920
If n is 2, you're over here.

00:45:23.920 --> 00:45:26.770
3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9, 10.

00:45:26.770 --> 00:45:29.510
So you can visualize how
the root is behaving,

00:45:29.510 --> 00:45:32.320
the complex root, by
looking at a complex plane.

00:45:32.320 --> 00:45:34.310
That other root works
just the same way,

00:45:34.310 --> 00:45:37.610
except it's negative so it
spins around the other way.

00:45:37.610 --> 00:45:40.330
So it's convenient to watch
the behavior of complex roots

00:45:40.330 --> 00:45:41.230
on a complex plane.

00:45:41.230 --> 00:45:44.800
That's not too surprising.

00:45:44.800 --> 00:45:48.340
What's slightly more
surprising is the idea

00:45:48.340 --> 00:45:51.880
of a real system that's made
out of adders and delays

00:45:51.880 --> 00:45:56.680
and that kind of stuff
generating a complex response.

